node.text:
Do you have what it takes to become a BARK ranger at Joshua Tree National Park? Watch this video to find out! BARK stands for: 
Bag your poop 
Always wear a leash 
Respect wildlife 
Know where you can go. 
For an audio described version of this video, please see the link in our bio.

Thinking of hiking with your four-legged friend? Learn some tips on how to be #DesertReady in today’s ranger moment on hiking with pets. 

Please remember that dogs are not permitted on trails. Pets must be leashed at all times and remain within 100 feet of a roadway (dirt or paved), picnic area, or campground.

For an audio described version of Hiking with Pets, please visit our YouTube channel, or see the link in our bio.

node.text: Today’s ranger minute is with Superintendent David Smith!

node.title: A Ranger Minute with Superintendent David Smith

node.accessibility_caption: A woman in a yellow shirt photographs the setting sun as it paints the landscape of Joshua trees and desert plants in a golden hue.

node.text:
Visitors come from all walks of life to hike, climb, or even photograph the landscapes. 

We want to know, why do you come to Joshua Tree National Park?

Photo: NPS / Emily Hassell

node.accessibility_caption: Group of people posing in front of boulders.

node.text:
Joshua tree visitor photo dump!📸

We love seeing our visitors share their experiences with others✨

node.accessibility_caption: Group of people posing in front of boulders.
Man posing in front of Joshua Tree and boulders.
Woman sitting, posing in front of boulders.
Man climbing a crack in the boulder.
Visitor jumping from one boulder to another.
Woman posing in front of boulders.
Woman walking away towards Joshua trees and boulders.
Group of visitors posing from a look out
Group of people by boulders admiring the sunset colors in the sky.
Rabbit lying under a bush

node.text:
Visiting Joshua Tree in the summertime? Seek shade. 

#RecreateResponsibly #PlanLikeAParkRanger #BehaveLikeARabbit

Photo: NPS / Shay Spatz

node.accessibility_caption: Stars and wispy clouds overhead with a dense patch of cactus below.

node.text:
We are looking forward to the 2021 Night Sky Festival this September 3-5! Enjoy the beauty of the night sky in the California Desert and learn about the amazing astronomy overhead. Check out the link in our bio for more information from the festival organizers.

Photo: NPS/Brad Sutton

node.accessibility_caption: Park Ranger sitting on rock and looking at a landscape of boulders, Joshua trees, and rock formations.

node.text:
*Ranger thinking to herself*  What is the meaning of life? Is it to sit and gaze upon beautiful places? To think deeply about how magical planet earth is? To ponder, how can I protect this cool globe full of rocks and trees and oceans and incredible stuff? 

NPS / Hannah Schwalbe

node.accessibility_caption: The night sky with a shooting star

node.text:
Happy Fourth of July weekend! This Independence Day, we’d like to be free from smoke and wildfires. Please be advised that fireworks are illegal to ignite in the park. The risk of a wildfire in our area is very high right now with the hot temps and our vegetation being extra dry and crispy. Campfires are also currently prohibited. However, the good news is you can still enjoy the colorful sunsets and shooting stars streaking across our dark night skies. 

#RecreateResponsibly

Photo: NPS / Brad Sutton

node.accessibility_caption: Una visitante caminando el sendero alrededor de cactus y plantas deserticas y montañas.

node.text:
Estando al aire libre y en la naturaleza tiene significados muy personales. Acampar, caminar por un sendero, manejar por el parque, tomar fotografías, ver el amanecer o el atardecer y muchas otras cosas más.

Lo más importante es disfrutar esos momentos, solos o con nuestros seres queridos. Nos complace preservar un lugar donde todos son bienvenidos mientras protegemos el espacio y sus contenidos. ¡Si necesitas ayuda en planificar tu viaje a Joshua Tree, chequea nuestra pagina en Español! (enlace en nuestra bio)😁

Que estás haciendo para mejorar los espacios naturales? 

#EncuentraTuParque #FindYourPark #GreatOutdoorsMonth 

Photo: NPS / Alessandra Puig-Santana

node.accessibility_caption: A hiker standing on a boulder looking out the landscape colored by the sunset hues.

node.text:
The outdoors means different things for different people. Camping, hiking, driving through the park, going out for a photography session. 

Most importantly, it means spending time with yourself or with those you love in a beautiful place. We are glad to preserve a place where all are welcomed and accepted meanwhile protecting this space and all it holds. 
 
How are you making the outdoors a better place? #GreatOutdoorsMonth #FindYourPark 

Photo: NPS / Alessandra Puig-Santana

node.accessibility_caption: A glowing tent is surrounded by a Joshua tree, large boulder, and the night sky.

node.text:
Although campfires aren’t allowed, camping is still lit! 

It is the best time to sleep under the stars, might be able to catch the Milky Way on a new moon night. 

Red lights won’t leave you with that intense campfire smell but gives enough light to see and tell creepy stories around the campsite. 

That’s still pretty fire, if you ask us! 

Due to high fire danger campfires, and all fires, are restricted in the park until further notice. Thanks for helping us keep Joshua Tree safe! 

Photos: NPS / Hannah Schwalbe, NPS / Kelsey Graczyk

Two people sit around a campfire ring at night. The campfire ring has a water bottle filled with a headlamp for light. Boulders and the night sky surround them.
Woman sitting on a large pile of boulders looking up at the Milky Way.

Tonight’s full moon is known as the Strawberry Moon. Spoiler alert: it will not look like an actual strawberry 😢  The June full moon gets its name from the time that wild strawberries typically ripen in North America. It’s also known as the Hot Moon, signifying the beginning of the hot season. This name makes more sense in Joshua Tree since we are entering our sizzling heat season and we still haven’t found any wild strawberries. Hot moonrise is at 8:27pm tonight in Joshua Tree. 

Photo: NPS / Lian Law

Alt text: Full moon rising above a horizon of a large boulder pile.
